Doc Del &amp; Joe:<br><br>
You are right, I forget that individuals looking at these sites might take this information and began to preach it as gospel truth. I should not have said &quot;MANY&quot; What I should have said, is; <br><br>
 &quot;Those,&quot; in Nam that caused their own self inflicted wounds, today, hide and feel that shame. They justify their cowardliness by demonstrating and speaking out against a just war...<br><br>
During my tour, I knew of only two such an incidents in the Corps. Two other times it involved Army personnel attached to our units. One Army individual shot himself in the leg on Hill 55 and another Army engineer assigned to us on Hill 65, who wasn't suppose to go out in the field, volunteered to go out with one of our squads. The squad leader did not know that and he allowed him to go out with them. That night while they were set up for an ambush he shot himself in the head and died. A month before I rotated out a Marine Sgt. Who fell in love with a local Vietnamese girl shot himself in her village when he found out she was VC.  I have checked the records and none of those incidents were reported as self-inflicted wounds. <br><br>
However by mid 1969, these type of incidents were occurring more frequent according to Marines I have spoken to that served during that time. A Sgt. who called me the other day confirmed that, stating that in those last days, it was a different Corps, volunteers had been replaced by draftees and discipline and unit integrity had been shot to hell. I do not know of any research into that area. I imagine it would also be hard to accurately document. As I said above, they were not documented as self-inflicted wounds.  I do not know about the other branches of the service. <br><br>
I do know that there is quite a difference between both services in the way we operated in Nam. Most of the time we operated in squad and platoon size operations while the Army did so in Company and battalion size operations. I remember looking at the Stars and Stripes and wishing I had joined the Army (I think that thought came to me as a form of jungle fatigue J ). Especially one day during operation Rock, we had been in heavy combat for days and as we crawled over Charlie's ridge on the other side the whole 1st Calvary diddy-bopping in the valley below.  Tanks, amtracks, jeeps, choppers everybody and their brothers on parade. <br><br>
The Corpsmen I referred to did his tour in the field but we became short having lost a Corpsmen on the 19th of November during Operation Foster. The Corpsmen who had been in the rear was send out to the field again. Our Platoon Lieutenant did not know his former history and once he found out the corpsmen had shot himself to get out of the bush the chopper was gone, unknown if he was ever court marshaled for that.<br><br>
I will point out again that the Corpsmen that served with us, every single one of them even those that beat us at cards every payday were held and I held them and still do today with the highest respect and honor. One bad apple does not spoil the courage of all the others that served with our unit.<br>
As far as the Sapper and Liberty Bridge, I guess you don't understand the humor we shared in Nam we laughed at the bridge being blown-up but I was there when they first started and when they finished building it. We laughed and ended up getting cold cuts from the Seabees mess hall that day for laughing about it. <br><br>
We joked around with the Seabees, we drank and sang and played cards together. They dug our trenches and cleared the area in front of my guns position with their big tractors so that I would have a clear field of fire. You had better believe that I would have done anything to have prevented the bridge from being blown up. There were a lot of things, that war fostered and we always kidded around we joked about their running around the compound in their short short camouflaged shorts and sunglasses while we patrolled the fields for Charlie. <br>
As far as the war in Viet Nam I believe we should have been there and in Hanoi.  What's wrong with Americans and American Vets and why we still feel the pain is that we haven't come to the realization yet,  that the real lesson we learned about the War in Vietnam was:, <br><br>
The Viet Nam war was just one more battle in the cold war. It was another operation, another battle that helped break down the power of the Soviet Union. I believe there should be a major campaign ribbon awarded to all Combat veterans that fought between 1947- 1972 because of this. Then perhaps Americans will begin to realize that we accomplished in Nam and while were at it. Leave a space in it fora bronze star because the Chinese battle is still ahead.  <br><br>

